WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
What I'm here to show you.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
There are a lot of other really great talks going on right now, so in the interest of

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
helping you make a fully informed decision about where you want to go, although it's

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
kind of stuck here now, I want to start by telling you kind of what I aim to get

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:26.000
across during this talk in the next, hopefully, less than 20 minutes.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.000
And my goal is to show you that the Shiny UI Editor is ready to be used in the real

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
world and not just toy scenarios.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
And I'm going to do this by walking you through building a Shiny app from scratch

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:42.000
using the UI Editor.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
So first I want to start with a little bit of context, which is around 10 years ago,

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.000
I remember building my first Shiny app.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And I remember I opened up RStudio and I clicked new app and there was a geyser

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
and then I took my code and I shoved it in there and then I never touched

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.000
the UI again because it was terrifying and I could barely get my code

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
in there, I'm not going to mess with the UI.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And then even eight or so years later, after I'd done enough Shiny and web development to actually get

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
a job on the Shiny team, I still found myself dreading

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
that initial prototype period where you have a cool API you want to

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
play with and you have to set up the UI, you have to

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
make things go where you want and that was just kind of annoying and sometimes you

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.000
just want to get that done really quickly. And so these two scenarios

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
really motivated the development of the UI Editor.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
And I think they can be summed up in kind of a general mission statement

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.000
because all great things such as Posit have a mission statement.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
And in researching how to give good talks, one of the things that I always

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
saw was you should read directly from the slides.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.000
So I'm going to do that here to read this mission statement. So the mission of the

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Shiny UI Editor is to help users turn their data analyses into

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
interactive Shiny dashboards. We want to generate app code that can be later

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
modified with or without the editor. And this is for both

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
those new to Shiny and also experts who want to expedite their development process.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Okay, so now we have context, we can start. But

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
just actually one more context slide, which is it's great to

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
have a mission statement and talk about all that stuff, but really what is the UI

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Editor? Maybe you don't know what it is. We haven't talked about it a ton.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So first and foremost, the UI Editor is a drag and drop visual editor for your

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Shiny's applications UIs. And it's focusing

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.000
specifically on the UI. It's a Shiny UI Editor.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Or does it actually? We'll get into that in a little bit.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
You can get the UI Editor via an R package

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:50.000
or if you're one of those crazy people that likes to use VS Code to write R,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
we have a VS Code extension. You can be one of the

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
single of people that have ever used it.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Okay, so now we can actually get started with the demo.

